'Only if this price increase continues for years and years would we approach something close to a property bubble in Berlin,' said Franz Eilers, head of research at the VDP mortgage bank association.

Last year 220 luxury condominiums were sold in Berlin, up from 185 in previous years, according to a report by consultancy bulwiengesa for Ziegert.

International clients now make up half of the buyers in the luxury market, said Ries.

Dubbed the 'epicenter of cool' and 'Brooklyn on the Spree' river by the foreign press, Berlin is seeing economic growth to match its trendy reputation. Its output grew 1.7 per cent in 2013, higher than the German national average.

